# =============================================================
# .cursorrules — Agentic Documentation System
# =============================================================
# These rules instruct Cursor AI to follow documentation-aware
# coding practices tied to our Confluence-based doc system.
# =============================================================

## Project Context
- This project uses an automated documentation pipeline.
- Code changes trigger a CI/CD workflow that updates Confluence pages.
- Confluence site: pikachu28.atlassian.net
- Confluence space: ED1
- Sandbox page ID: 688129

## Commit Message Rules
- Always include `[DocUpdate: <PAGE_ID>]` in commit messages when changes
  affect documented features.
- Format: `git commit -m "feat: description [DocUpdate: 688129]"`
- If multiple pages are affected, include multiple tags:
  `[DocUpdate: 688129] [DocUpdate: 123456]`

## Code Standards
- Follow PEP 8 for Python files.
- All public functions must have docstrings.
- Use type hints for all function parameters and return values.
- Keep functions under 50 lines.

## Documentation Awareness
- When asked about project standards, reference Confluence documentation
  using @Confluence MCP integration.
- Before implementing a feature, check if specs exist in the Engineering Docs
  space (key: ED1) on Confluence.
- Use the command: @Confluence "search for [feature name] specs"

## Testing Requirements
- All new features must have corresponding unit tests.
- Tests must pass before pushing (CI/CD only syncs docs on success).
- Run: `python -m pytest tests/ -v` before committing.

## File Organization
- `/src/` — Application source code
- `/tests/` — Unit and integration tests
- `/scripts/` — Automation and utility scripts
- `/docs/` — Local documentation (synced to Confluence)
